# üêû Bug report

### Is this a regression?

<!-- Did this behavior use to work in the previous version? -->
<!-- ‚úçÔ∏è--> Yes, the previous version in which this bug was not present was: 7.x


### Description

The :host-context pseudo class emulation appears to have changed from version 7.x to 8.x. In 7.x versions the following code:
```
:host-context(.test)my-app {
    color: purple;
}
```

would result in the following after compiling:
```
.testmy-app[_nghost-xti-c0], .test my-app[_nghost-xti-c0] {
    color: purple;
}
```

The first would not match anything but the second would.

In 8.x this now results in the following after compiling:
```
.test[_nghost-xti-c0] my-app[_ngcontent-xti-c0], .test [_nghost-xti-c0] my-app[_ngcontent-xti-c0] {
    color: purple;
}
```
In this case, niether match. However, in both versions, if changed to a class instead of an element it works correctly. So in both 7.x and 8.x versions the following:

```
:host-context(.test).my-class {
    color: purple;
}
```

would result in the following after compiling:
```
.test.my-class[_nghost-xti-c0], .test .my-class[_nghost-xti-c0] {
    color: purple;
}
```
So it appears as if the :host-context selector is now only properly emulated when using a class selector but not when using an element selector.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction
7.x working correctly: https://github.com/brianmtreese/host-context-element-selector-issue-7-x

8.x working differently: https://github.com/brianmtreese/host-context-element-selector-issue-8-x


